			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">In general, coordinates based on the center of something makes object-object collision detection easier if objects have different sizes. For example, if you have one object 14 pixels across and another 4 pixels across, they overlap if their centers are within (14 + 4)/2 = 9 pixels of each other. With top left, the collision happens if the distance is between -14 and 4 pixels, which makes it easier to get the sign wrong.<br /><br />Plus there's a reason why objects have a center of mass, not a top-left of mass.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

